<TEXT>
some witnesses who testified before a 
congressional panel on influence peddling at the housing and urban 
development department have come dangerously close to perjuring 
themselves a republican member of the subcommittee said wednesday 
meanwhile rep tom lantos dcalif the panels chairman said 
he has met with lawyers for a key witness who has refused to 
testify but lantos would not say whether the discussions included a 
request for or offer of immunity 
the hearings before the house government operations subcommittee 
on housing and employment were to resume thursday with fred bush a 
1988 fundraiser for george bushs presidential effort among those 
scheduled to testify fred bush unrelated to the president 
testified may 25 and the subcommittee recalled him 
after more than a month of hearings on allegations that bigname 
republicans profited handsomely by using their connections to land 
multimilliondollar contracts at hud rep christopher shays 
rconn said in an interview that some contradictions have emerged 
but he refused to specify what they were or who made them 
i think there are some persons who are dangerously close to 
perjuring themselves shays said we have some conflicting 
testimony 
shays a member of the subcommittee has been outspoken in his 
criticism of the management of hud during the eight years of the 
reagan administration 
he said that some of the conflicts among witnesses also may be 
due to poor memory or misunderstanding the questions 
but lantos while not disagreeing with shays said he would wait 
until the hearings are nearly over before saying whether any of the 
witnesses had lied 
i think everything that chris shays says may well prove to 
be the case lantos said but i would prefer to make any 
comments along those lines much later than at this stage of the 
game 
obviously in a number of instances we have had people claiming 
not knowing not remembering and there comes a point where this 
appears less and less plausible lantos said in an interview 
ive tried my very best to give the witnesses the benefit of 
the doubt and caution them when i thought they were on dangerous 
territory lantos said 
witnesses said they made contact with deborah gore dean who was 
then executive assistant to housing secretary samuel pierce jr to 
get approval for their projects seeking funds from hud for 
rehabilitating rundown housing for the poor in some of these 
cases the funds for fixing up the property rent subsidies and tax 
credits ran into the tens of millions of dollars 
the witnesses have said that ms deans support for a project was 
crucial in gaining department approval contact with her often was 
made through former hud employees or by wellplaced republicans 
such as former interior secretary james watt who hired out their 
services for sixfigure fees as consultants 
another prominent republican who received a consulting fee for 
helping a project win federal housing funds was fred brown a new 
york businessman and chairman of the national black republican 
council the new york times said in thursday editions 
a 1987 audit by hud investigators questioned browns 50000 fee 
for consulting work on behalf of new haven conn in its successful 
bid for a 10 million federal urban development action grant 
the audit said there was insufficient data to determine whether 
the fee is reasonable and that this type of service was necessary 
a lawyer for brown joshua s vogel said his client was 
instrumental in obtaining the new haven grant through his contacts 
with ms dean the newspaper said 
in his earlier testimony fred bush whose company made 268000 
as consultant on a hud project said that he too sought ms deans 
support at the department but said that he was not personally 
acquainted with her 
in her appearance before the subcommittee last month ms dean 
refused to testify citing her constitutional protection against 
selfincrimination 
lantos said he remained hopeful that ms dean would testify in 
which case some of the questions of controversy among the various 
businesses will come out into the open 
asked if he has discussed a deal with ms deans attorneys under 
which she would be granted immunity for her testimony before the 
panel lantos replied i can confirm that i have met with them 
but i am not liberty to discuss what they talked to me about and 
what i talked to them about 
ms dean contacted by telephone declined to talk about meetings 
between her attorneys and the subcommittee she said that she had 
been spending her time examining a box full of documents recently 
obtained from hud 
one of her attorneys charles leeper also confirmed meetings 
with the subcommittee but would not elaborate 
</TEXT>
