strike from belva coal co a pittston mine near logan wva 
on monday us district judge glen williams tried to put a 
financial roadblock in the way of the miners he fined the union and 
two officers 240000 for organizing the convoys and he promised to 
levy fines totaling 120000 for each day the convoys continue 
on tuesday a federal judge in west virginia ruled that the 
nearly 43000 coal miners on wildcat strikes in nine states are 
violating us labor law and ordered them to return to work 
but the wildcat strikers said they have a permanent stake in what 
happens to the 1900 union members on strike against pittston 
pittston broke away from an association of coal companies that 
signed a national contract with the umw last year and miners 
believe that if the union loses its dispute with pittston their 
companies may follow suit and lower their benefits pensions and job 
security 
if everybody else does what pittston is doing were all up a 
creek evans said 
he sleeps on a plastic sheet on the ground in a tent with a dozen 
