sweltering heat and suffocating humidity of summertime washington 
thats not stiff enough howe replied he thought a moment 
and added i wouldnt want to be up there with someone whos 
burned a flag 
howe and his nine helpers raise and lower an average of more than 
350 flags each weekday they sometimes work on weekends to meet 
requests for flags to be flown on special anniversary dates that 
happen to fall on a saturday or sunday 
the heaviest demand occurs on such patriotic holidays as memorial 
day and the fourth of july when as many as 1200 flags have been 
flown in a single day 
using three small flagpoles on the roof of the house side of the 
capitol they raise a flag for a few seconds lower it and fold it 
back into its box in bad weather they use six ropes equipped with 
flag hooks under the sheltered skirt of the capitol dome to fly 
their flags 
the practice began in 1937 when a dozen flags were flown over 
the capitol for legislators constituents last year the number had 
risen to more than 114000 altogether more than 14 million flags 
have been flown over the capitol to meet public requests in the past 
halfcentury 
down in the flag room in the capitol basement the busy 
staging area for the flag flying operation boxed flags are stacked 
to the ceilings in four cramped rooms decorated with portraits of 
betsy ross and a plaque bearing a poem titled our flag 
chris benza who has run the flag room for 28 years said the 
public demand for the stars and stripes is growing so fast that 
shes been promised a fifth storage room to handle the crush 
the last few weeks weve been overwhelmed with flag requests 
and i dont know why said william f raines administrative 
assistant to the architect of the capitol who oversees the flag 
program raines said the trend began before the supreme courts june 
22 decision 
