<TEXT>
a fatherly figure sentenced to death more 
than 40 years ago for his communist activities holds the key to a 
political deadlock that has gripped greece since elections failed to 
form a government 
harilaos florakis the 75yearold leader of the coalition of the 
left and progress has suddenly been thrust into the limelight as he 
approaches the twilight of his political career 
florakis jailed for 17 years after the countrys civil war has 
spent his entire career criticizing the united states and its bases 
in this nato nation and pressing each government in office to 
withdraw from the alliance 
his coalition dominated by florakis promoscow greek communist 
party kke won 28 parliamentary seats in the june 18 general 
election enough to play the kingmakers role 
the incumbent panhellenic socialist movement pasok took 125 
seats and the conservative new democracy won 145 but neither can 
govern without leftist suppport because a majority is needed in the 
300member parliament 
florakis has become the grand old man of greek politics no one 
could imagine years ago that a communist would play such an 
important role in our political life said a conservative deputy 
who spoke on condition of anonymity 
florakis emerged as a leader in the illegal greek communist 
movement after fighting alongside national resistance forces against 
the nazis during world war ii 
two years after the nazis left communists under the guise of a 
greek liberation army attempted to seize power kicking off a bloody 
threeyear civil war that ended in 1949 and a humiliating defeat for 
the communists 
florakis then a 33yearold idealist with training as a 
telegraphist led the communist 1st regiment of the greek liberation 
army and was condemned to death by a military tribunal for his role 
in the civil war 
like thousands of communists who fought and lost against the 
americanbacked greek nationalist army he was imprisoned others 
were exiled to barren islands or remote villages thousands of 
communists also fled to east bloc countries and the soviet union 
never knowing when they could return home 
but time healed many wounds as communist exiles slowly came back 
to greece in december 1982 premier andreas papandreou head of a 
socialist administration allowed mass repatriation in an effort at 
national reconciliation 
florakis spent 17 years in prison for his communist activities 
which should have made him bitter but colleagues say he holds no 
grudge 
the pipesmoking silverhaired florakis a widower who never had 
children looks more today like a college professor with his 
conservative dress 
in a spirit of political change conservative premier constantine 
