hundreds of imprisoned chinese activists are in 
danger of being executed on the whim of officialdom and their 
safety may depend on protests from abroad amnesty international 
said today 
the international human rights organization said its fears for 
hundreds of people detained since the prodemocracy movement was 
violently crushed june 4 were based on chinas notorious record 
of executions and unfair trials 
chinese authorities have announced 27 executions since soldiers 
killed hundreds of unarmed civilians in clearing central beijing of 
protesters 
amnesty said there have been 33 executions though unconfirmed 
unofficial reports estimated that hundreds have been put to 
death about 1800 people have been arrested 
the group said chinas practice of verdict first trial 
second resulted in as many as 30000 people being executed in an 
anticrime drive between 1983 and 1987 many after unfair and 
summary trials 
offenses ranged from murder and rape to stealing bicycles 
hanging political slogans and stealing museum antiques 
in such a situation the lives of defendants facing capital 
charges depend totally on the whim of officialdom amnesty said in 
a statement their only hope may be the voices raised on their 
behalf outside china by governments and ordinary people around the 
world 
the group rejected the notion that chinese authorities are 
impervious to foreign pleas for restraint noting that recent 
efforts to reassure visiting trade delegations shows their concern 
for world opinion 
those executed this month were charged with violent offenses but 
there is no way of determining whether the charges bore any 
relation to reality because of the swiftness of the proceedings 
and the absence of adequate safeguards for the defense amnesty said 
our concerns are heightened by the number of people believed to 
have been arrested after the nationwide demonstrations in may and 
early june and the danger of many of them being charged with the 
wide battery of capital offenses provided for by chinese law it 
said 
china has announced that 10 people were executed because of the 
unrest and accused the 17 others of seriously endangering public 
order 
amnesty said trials and appeals are usually mere formalities 
in china that people are often executed within days of arrest and 
that there is no presumption of innocence in chinese law 
it said many accused are not given enough time to prepare a 
defense and that lawyers may meet clients only when the indictment 
is served in death penalty and other serious cases the law permits 
courts to give a copy of the indictment to defendants only when the 
trial starts it said 
the world must make the chinese government aware that human 
rights violations on the scale of the past few weeks will not be 
forgotten said amnesty winner of the 1977 nobel peace prize 
