<TEXT>
long island lighting co shareholders have 
overwhelmingly approved a deal that could make shoreham the first 
licensed nuclear power plant in the nation to be abandoned before 
coming on line 
the agreement approved wednesday by 95 percent of the 
shareholders calls for the utility to sell shoreham for 1 to the 
long island power authority a state agency 
in exchange a tentative rate hike schedule was established under 
which the company gets 11 increases over 10 years of about 5 percent 
each the state public service commission must approve each increase 
the federal nuclear regulatory commission still must give 
permission to the company to sell the plant and to long island power 
authority to dismantle it 
deputy secretary of energy w henson moore said the shareholders 
vote is not a fatal blow to the shoreham nuclear power plant nor 
is it a fatal blow to the energy future for the people of long 
island 
moore vowed to preserve the option of using shoreham in the 
future by trying to thwart the transfer of the plant to the state 
agency 
long island lighting chairman william catacosinos told 
shareholders he doubts the energy department can legally block the 
sale or keep the plant from being dismantled 
gov mario cuomo called the federal governments sudden 
interest regarding shoreham all the more troubling in view of 
the unfolding scandal surrounding its own nuclear facilities and the 
threats they pose to public safety and national security 
energy officials say nuclear power is essential to reducing the 
countrys need for imported oil long island lighting is almost 
entirely dependent on foreign oil 
in april the nrc granted a license to shoreham to operate at 
full power previously the plant was licensed to operate at 5 
percent shoreham was completed in 1985 10 years behind schedule 
at a cost of 55 billion it was supposed to cost 261 million 
other plants have been abandoned before completion 
the campaign to close shoreham centered on contentions by state 
and local officials that long island could never be safely evacuated 
in the event of a nuclear accident 
most of the 20 shareholders who spoke at the companys annual 
meeting denounced the plants demise but catacosinos called for an 
end to the uncertainty surrounding shoreham which nearly bankrupted 
the utility in 1984 
the shareholders also approved settlement of a classaction 
lawsuit under the racketeer influenced and corrupt organizations act 
in which suffolk county charged that long island lighting had lied 
about costs and the progress of shoreham to get rate hikes 
a federal jury convicted the utility but a judge threw out the 
case a lawyer for the ratepayers settled the case for 390 million 
to be refunded to ratepayers in monthly bills over 10 years 
meantime the nrc has begun its investigation of improper control 
room procedures at the nuclear power plant in seabrook nh during 
last weeks abrupt shutdown of lowpower testing 
the 6 billion reactor was shut down after a valve in the 
nonnuclear part of the plant malfunctioned nrc observers said they 
suggested several times that the plant be shut down before seabrook 
operators responded 
seabrook officials have acknowledged it took about five minutes 
for operators to react and that they did not follow proper 
procedures 
