charles haughey failed to win reelection 
as prime minister thursday losing a parliamentary vote by 86 votes 
to 78 
the impasse pushes ireland into tricky constitutional terrain 
and could force state president patrick hillery whose post is 
largely ceremonial to make the next move 
haughey needed 83 votes but mustered only the 78 of his fianna 
fail party and independent lawmaker tom foxe one legislator 
abstained 
the 166member dail or parliament voted on other candidates 
but rejected all of them alan dukes leader of the opposition fine 
gael party was defeated 10361 with one abstention 
proceedings halted for two hours haughey proposed adjourning 
until monday but opposition lawmakers demanded he resign as party 
leader and make way for a new candidate 
if no compromise is reached the president must decide whether to 
give haughey another chance to muster a majority or an option 
seen as less likely order another election 
the crisis arose from the june 15 election which haughey called 
in an unsuccessful bid to win an outright majority 
haughey had led ireland with a minority government for more than 
two years with tacit support of the fine gael and progressive 
democrat parties 
he called the election when opinion polls showed him likely to 
win a majority but his ratings slid in the days before the vote 
and he won 77 seats four fewer than he had held 
