shells exploded in beiruts moslem and 
christian sectors today as syrian and christian gunners fought 
despite a call by arab leaders for a truce six people were killed 
and 26 wounded police said 
the whooshing sound of outgoing rockets and the thuds of 
exploding shells rocked the city smoke and dust billowed from 
several targeted areas 
by police count 380 people have been killed and 1497 wounded 
since march 8 when the current round of violence broke out pitting 
christian army cmdr gen michel aouns troops against syrian and 
allied militia forces 
a police spokesman said todays fatalities included two civilians 
killed in moslem west beirut when a shell crashed on their car the 
two were driving on a seaside boulevard where the syrians have 
several artillery batteries firing on christian districts 
a civilian also was killed at west beiruts barbir hospital near 
the capitals dividing green line when the facility took several 
direct rounds from christian gunners said the spokesman who could 
not be named in line with standing regulations 
he said the three other civilians were killed in christian east 
beirut 
a hospital official speaking on condition he not be named said 
the man killed at the hospital had taken refuge there after shelling 
started while he was in the street 
syrian artillery batteries also shelled the christian coastline 
north of the city to maintain a blockade of the enclave home to 
about 1 million christians 
christian radio stations interrupted their programs to flash 
reports of the renewed syrian shelling and urge the population to 
take the needed precautions 
this is the way the syrians responded to the ceasefire called 
by the tripartite arab committee the voice of lebanon radio said 
the truce was requested tuesday by king hassan ii of morocco 
king fahd of saudi arabia and president chadli bendjedid of algeria 
the three leaders concluding talks in oran algeria also called 
for lifting the siege of the christian enclave it invited lebanons 
parliament to meet outside the country to forge a settlement to the 
14yearold civil war 
an arab league leaders summit in morocco last month asked the 
three heads of state to find a settlement to the civil war by 
november 
christian and moslem leaders have welcomed the call by the three 
arab leaders for an end to violence in all its forms but 
differed on whether lebanons parliament should meet overseas 
christian parliament members in general have opposed meeting 
outside lebanon saying if the siege were lifted and crossing 
gateways reopened there would be no need to travel 
