the united nations has imported more 
than 20 tons of arms and ammunition including 15600 hand grenades 
for its peacekeeping forces in namibia officials said thursday 
kenyan army brig daniel opande deputy commander of the force 
said the consignment is a normal entitlement for un troops in 
such a situation he did not say why it was needed 
the shipment including 200 antitank rockets and 2600 mortar 
shells is destined mainly for kenyan and malaysian combat troops 
with some explosives to go to an australian engineering unit 
according to die republikein newspaper among other duties the 
australians are building refugee centers and schools 
thousands of un personnel from more than 40 countries are in 
namibia to supervise a yearlong transition to independence for this 
former german colony 
they include 4500 troops among them combat battalions of about 
900 men each from malaysia and kenya and 600 from finland deployed 
in the northern part of the country where a unsponsored 
ceasefire ended a 23year bush war earlier this year 
die republikein said the arms arrived in midapril at walvis bay 
port in namibia which south africa refuses to give up the paper 
printed copies of the import licenses 
un peacekeepers normally patrol report truce violations and 
stand between belligerent forces to prevent new fighting 
no fighting has been reported in namibia since a sudden 
infiltration of southwest africa peoples organization guerrillas 
triggered bloody clashes with south african forces that ended april 
1 south africa since has withdrawn all its military from namibia as 
part of a regional peace accord that includes the withdrawal of 
50000 cuban troops from angola 
the kenyans and malaysians patrol the namibiaangola border 
scene of the earlier hostilities the finns who brought their own 
arms supplies are deployed farther east 
