<TEXT>
students at tufts university can wear tshirts with 
raunchy messages in dorm rooms and on campus lawns but not in 
classrooms under a new policy that officials said thursday tries to 
balance free speech with decorum 
we feel its our obligation to say that there are no 
constituencies that are fair game said dean of students bobbie 
knable 
the tshirt zones were created after a male student marketed 200 
tshirts that gave 15 reasons why beer is better than women at 
tufts all disparaging to women one of the more printable lines 
was hangovers go away 
there were complaints about it knable said the tshirt 
dealer was placed on probation and sentenced to 50 hours of 
community service which was later revoked officials of the private 
liberal arts school then decided to draft a policy curtailing the 
bodily display of hostile or derogatory slogans 
the new rules which take effect this fall could involve some 
fast changing for instance a student might wear a risque tshirt 
in his own room then cover up the offending portion on his walk 
through the dormitory common area before reaching the campus lawn a 
free area 
but knable says the circuitous policy stems from efforts to 
comply with free speech rights 
students in classrooms or dormitory common areas cant escape 
looking at the offending message so the tshirts are banned she 
said but dormitory rooms are private and general campus grounds 
cant be controlled 
we didnt expect that we could protect our students from all of 
the manifestations of bigotry or prejudice knable said 
the writing of the policy stirred lively debate on campus the 
final decision on what constitutes a derogatory slogan will be made 
on a casebycase basis she said 
we really tried to narrow the definition of offensive to 
derogatory and demeaning knable said there are a lot of ideas 
that people will encounter on campuses in a diverse community that 
will be offensive to them and we are not trying to protect people 
from ideas she said 
knable said the policy is intended to be more of a deterrent than 
a disciplinary tool if complaints are lodged with the dean of 
students the matter will be taken to a panel of faculty and 
students possible penalties might be probation or community service 
knable said officials at tufts known for its foreign policy 
department dont expect to have to enforce their penalty frequently 
this fall 
its not as if we are a campus in which we expect the most 
virulent kind of things will happen and happen frequently its just 
that we are still a part of the world she said 
