<TEXT>
britain will argue vigorously that china should 
keep its army out of central hong kong after the colony reverts to 
chinese sovereignty in 1997 a british official said thursday 
the senior official who spoke on condition of anonymity briefed 
reporters as foreign secretary sir geoffrey howe prepared to travel 
to hong kong on saturday to reaffirm britains commitment to the 
colony 
howes schedule during his threeday visit includes meetings with 
officials and residents 
concern among hong kongs population of 57 million about life 
under chinese rule has increased since june 3 when the chinese 
government ordered thousands of troops into beijing to crush the 
sevenweek prodemocracy movement 
we shall be arguing very strongly that it would be very 
misguided of china to put their troops in the center of hong kong 
the british official said 
under the 1984 joint declaration the british pact with china 
that guarantees at least 50 years of autonomy for hong kong under 
chinese rule authorities in hong kong are responsible for public 
order 
this is not the responsibility of people in khaki uniforms 
that is what we have to underline in thick thick ink the 
official said 
chinese troops stationed in hong kong have to abide by hong kong 
law the official added 
he said the questions of how many chinese troops would be allowed 
in hong kong and where they would be stationed are still subject to 
negotiation 
britain will raise the issues during the next round of talks on 
hong kong britain postponed the july meeting because of the 
crackdown on the prodemocracy movement 
no decision has been made on when the meetings will be resumed 
but i would think certainly before the end of the year maybe in the 
autumn the official said 
under the joint declaration meetings are to be held three times 
a year and britain plans to stick to the letter of the agreement 
if we want china to do the same the official said 
since the crackdown began some hong kong residents have called 
for the joint declaration to be torn up 
the official said britain has no intention of doing that but 
wants to change a few things in a draft constitution under which 
china will govern capitalist hong kong as a special administrative 
region after the british withdraw 
the times of london quoted a report by the powerful house of 
commons foreign affairs committee as saying the british government 
should mobilize an international effort to resettle hong kong 
residents should china violate the joint declaration 
the committee recommends that limited categories of residents be 
given the right to settle in britain but rejects such rights for 
all 325 million british passport holders the newspaper said 
the report to be published friday also calls for an 
acceleration of the timetable for introducing democracy in the 
colony so it is firmly established before 1997 the times said 
