<TEXT>
president bush reviving a topic buried by 
public outcry four months ago promised thursday to work with 
congress to get members a pay raise he didnt say how big the raise 
should be 
in a speech focused on another prickly issue campaign finance 
reform the president mentioned the payhike question only briefly 
he said he would send congress legislation in a few days seeking 
to ban the outside income senators and representatives earn from 
speaking engagements a restriction many have said they would accept 
only if accompanied by higher salaries 
bush said he would work with congress on the development of 
details for increasing the pay of those in congress as well as other 
senior employees of the executive branch 
he already has endorsed a 25 percent pay increase for judges and 
the legislation he sends to capitol hill on outside income will 
include a specific increase amount for senior officials white house 
counsel boyden gray said he refused to disclose the amount 
bush described his campaign finance package which includes 
provisions to abolish most political action committees as an 
effort to cut special interest influence in politics and make 
campaigns more fair by decreasing the significant advantages of 
incumbents 
since a majority of incumbents are democratic however the 
proposals have the effect of helping the republican partys chances 
to improve its standing 
we need reforms that curtail special interest influence 
enhance the role of the individual and strengthen the parties 
bush said to an audience of congressional interns we must do more 
to truly clean up the system 
his proposals also include curtailing congressional franking 
privileges which he said pay for mass mailings that amount to 
political advertising and doing away with gerrymandering the 
drawing of crazyquilt congressional districts to help certain 
candidates 
the president declined to endorse public financing of 
congressional campaigns or overall spending limits which have been 
urged by democratic officials as well as private groups 
democratic national committee chairman ronald h brown said that 
in failing to call for spending limits the presidents campaign 
finance bill ought to be labeled the fat cat protection act of 1989 
he wants to make it easier to give republican candidates access to 
big money contributors 
bob dreyfuss spokesman for the advocacy group public citizen 
said that in dismissing public financing and spending limits bush 
tends to really allow the people with money to have undue 
influence in politics 
house speaker thomas s foley dwash has already promised the 
house will produce an ethics and campaign reform package this 
session and he said bush was joining the bandwagon late 
i want to say this as kindly as i can we welcome the 
presidents involvement but he is not leading this matter he is 
joining an issue which the democrats and the congressional 
republicans have been participating in and actively since the 
first of the year he said 
bush said public financing would exclude individuals from the 
political process by denying them the opportunity to contribute and 
spending limits would discourage them from contributing 
congress has repeatedly rejected proposals for campaign finance 
changes but republican supporters from capitol hill said they hoped 
bushs leadership and heightened public opinion on the issue would 
change that this time around 
bush proposed to bar corporations unions and trade associations 
from financially sponsoring political action committees effectively 
abolishing most of the pacs that contributed more than 151 million 
to congressional candidates in the 198788 election cycle 
that move bush said would help free our electoral system from 
the grip of special interests 
he also proposed 
reducing the percandidate contribution limit for the remaining 
pacs from the current 5000 to 2500 
banning a practice known as bundling in which a group 
gathers individuals contributions and delivers them to candidates 
rather than having the individual donate directly 
requiring full disclosure of soft money contributions and 
spending 
soft money refers generally to corporate and labor money that 
is barred for federal candidates but finds its want into the system 
when the funds are contributed to political parties which then help 
the candidates 
touching on an area that has bedeviled the federal election 
commission for three years with no resolution bush called for 
guidelines on how to differentiate between such money and funds 
raised within federal standards for generic activity such as voter 
registration and getoutthevote efforts that benefit both federal 
and nonfederal candidates 
bush would decrease the advantage of incumbents by 
restricting franking privileges which allow members of congress 
to send mail to their constituents free blanket constituency 
mailings and newsletters for instance would be banned 
curtailing gerrymandering methods of drawing political district 
lines to benefit one political party or group over another the 
districts would have to be drawn according to geographical and 
community boundaries said a senior administration official 
no single factor is more important in restoring competitive 
elections bush said than doing away with the crazy quilt 
district maps that have been drawn in some states to group voters in 
a blocks that benefit one party 
the redistricting is controlled by state legislatures 28 of 
which are controlled by democrats to eight by republicans thirteen 
are split and nebraska has a nonpartisan onechamber legislature 
more than doubling the amount of money that political parties 
are allowed to give to their candidates for house and senate for 
senate races the amount currently ranges from 92000 to some 15 
million depending on state population since incumbents are able to 
attract far more money than challengers in private contributions 
this provision would mean more to the cashstrapped gop challengers 
banning carrying over campaign funds from one election to the 
next thus requiring congressional candidates to return leftover 
funds to the contributors or give the money to the political parties 
or the government 
</TEXT>
