<TEXT>
legislation calling for a yearlong moratorium 
on oil exploration along vast stretches off americas coast 
including new england and alaska won approval thursday from a key 
house committee where members repeatedly cited concern about 
possible oil spills 
the bush administration immediately promised to fight the curbs 
probably in the senate saying mandatory prohibitions on offshore 
oil exploration would stifle badly needed domestic petroleum 
development 
we believe they congressionallyimposed bans are a delaying 
tactic said interior secretary manuel lujan 
the action by the house appropriations committee on a fiscal 1990 
spending bill for the interior department would put a temporary halt 
to oil exploration in alaskas bristol bay one of the nations 
premier fishing centers where the government already has sold a 
half dozen exploratory leases for 94 million 
the legislation also would extend or impose prohibitions on oil 
or gas exploration off california off the everglades of 
southwestern florida in the georges bank off new england and along 
a 50mile wide coastal strip that stretches from rhode island to 
maryland 
this is a critical victory at a critical time said rep leon 
panetta dcalif chairman of the house budget committee the 
message is clear we will not tolerate more tragic oil spills 
an exploratory drilling moratorium already has been in effect on 
leases in many of those areas but the ban would be extended to the 
center coast of california and to the midatlantic region under the 
legislation it also would ensure that no exploratory activity is 
taken before october 1990 the end of the next fiscal year 
the 116 billion interior money bill which prohibits any money 
being spent on oil lease in the areas cited cleared the house 
committee by a voice vote after two amendments aimed at softening 
the impact of the oil exploration moratorium were defeated by votes 
of 2922 and 2822 
the first amendment would have deleted reference to bristol bay 
while the second would have allowed a variety of prelease 
activities off the california coast although actual exploratory 
drilling would still have been put on hold 
opponents of the bristol bay drilling ban argued that oil 
development in the pristine alaska waters home for a 1 billion 
fishing industry is needed to keep america free of having to 
depend increasingly on oil imports 
what were doing in the name of the environment is cutting off 
our energy sources were going to have brownouts and then there 
