alan woods administrator of the agency for 
international development aid in the reagan and bush 
administrations and a strong advocate of linking us assistance to 
economic reform died thursday of cancer at the age of 43 
he was also a former deputy us trade representative and a 
proponent of open trade policies 
in one of his last appearances woods on may 12 argued for 
concentrating us aid assistance on what he called sustainable 
development instead of being given away woods said aid should 
be a temporary bridge to private support and selfsustained 
growth 
in the trade post which woods held from 1985 to 1987 he was the 
reagan administrations chief strategist in dealing with congress on 
trade legislation and the lead negotiator with canada on lumber and 
also on us market access to portugal and spain 
then at aid beginning in 1987 woods promoted marketoriented 
economic policies believing they and open trade held the key to 
progress in developed and undeveloping countries alike 
woods whose first name was michael was a native of mexico mo 
and served in 197374 as chief of staff for christopher bond then 
the governor of missouri and now a us senator 
