a new compound called amitraz has proved 
effective against tiny mites that infest the breathing tubes of 
honey bees the agriculture department said thursday 
amitraz was developed in europe and is approved for use in the 
united states against ticks and lice of cattle and hogs and against 
certain mites that infest pears said entomologist william t wilson 
of the departments agricultural research service 
in early tests at the agencys honey bee research laboratory in 
weslaco texas wilson found that amitraz was at least 90 percent 
effective against the tracheal mite acarapis woodi 
the compound was also effective against the varroa mite another 
major bee parasite he said 
wilson said amitraz needs approval of the environmental 
protection agency before it can be marketed for tracheal mite 
control 
