the house banking committee urged president 
bush on thursday to put more pressure on private us and foreign 
banks to negotiate larger debt forgiveness agreements with mexico 
the committee on a 419 vote approved a resolution saying the 
reduction should be big enough to permit mexico to achieve a 
sufficiently positive rate of economic growth to ensure the 
maintenance of social and economic stability 
the resolution also urged us banking regulators the federal 
reserve board and the comptroller of the currency to make banks 
set aside more reserves for covering impaired foreign debt 
mexico asked for a 55 percent reduction in the 54 billion it 
owes private lenders about 15 billion of it to us banks after 
treasury secretary nicholas f brady unveiled his third world debt 
relief plan in march 
the banks led by citicorp manufacturers hanover and chemical 
bank in new york and bank of america in san francisco initially 
offered to share in a 15 percent to 20 percent reduction 
even with its decision last week to extend an antiinflation 
austerity program for another nine months mexico has claimed the 
banks offer still would take too much of its foreign exchange 
earnings to permit a resumption of growth in its domestic economy 
the two sides are negotiating and sources close to the talks say 
discussions are centering on a debt reduction target in the range of 
30 percent to 40 percent 
the committee resolution is a reaffirmation of bradys plan 
which offers the private banks governmentbacked guarantees they 
will be paid interest on the remaining balance but only if the 
banks voluntarily reduce the debt third world countries owe them 
the administration has been hoping that a general agreemen could 
be reached before midjuly so bush could proclaim the brady plan a 
success at the paris economic summit 
but the split vote by the house committee indicated a growing 
sentiment that the bush administration initiative isnt working 
some lawmakers particularly republicans are beginning to 
distance themselves from it a few are echoing remarks by european 
officials that the plan amounts to little more than a taxpayer 
bailout through the world bank and international monetary fund 
of bad loans made by private banks 
wheres the money coming from asked rep toby roth rwis 
its coming out of the hide of our taxpayers 
rep jim bunning rky said the private banks have a duty to 
write off third world loans that have turned sour 
roth and bunning were among the six of the 20 republicans and 
three of the 30 democrats on the committee to vote against the 
resolution 
