britains first astronaut will team up with two 
soviet cosmonauts on a trip to the orbiting soviet space station mir 
in 1991 under an agreement signed thursday 
the astronaut job open to a man or a woman is to appear in 
advertisements in the british press in the next few days 
the british consortium behind mission is trying to raise 25 
million to cover the astronauts costs project director malcolm 
mageebrown told a moscow news conference 
the mission named juno does not rely on state support of any 
kind making it unique in space history mageebrown said 
the consortium britain in space ltd hopes to find the funding 
through corporate sponsorships contracts for scientific experiments 
in orbit and the sale of broadcast and publishing rights he said 
experiments the astronaut could perform might reap benefits for 
pharmaceutical companies biology and basic science said heinz 
wolff the projects science chief 
the project pairs the british consortium with glavkosmos the 
soviet space agency glavkosmos is already planning to send an 
austrian and a japanese journalist up to mir in 1990 or 1991 
director alexander dunayev said 
two british astronaut candidates will be selected by november 
one to fly aboard the orbiting station and the other to serve as 
understudy they will train in a glavkosmos center for 18 months to 
learn russian practice experiments and prepare physically for the 
flight organizers said 
candidates should be between 21 and 40 physically fit have a 
degree in science and an aptitude for handling delicate scientific 
equipment said vicemarshal peter howard in charge of astronaut 
selection marshal is former director of the british air force 
institute of aviation medicine 
dunayev said glavkosmos expects to barely cover its costs on the 
juno mission but is interested in developing international 
cooperation in the commercial space business 
the anglosoviet project was named for juno the roman goddess of 
marriage because it marks the start of a very special 
relationship between glavkosmos and the british space 
administration mageebrown said 
the united state was never in the running for the contract with 
the british wolff said there were no other offers of the kind 
the soviet union made from countries with human launch 
capabilities he said 
mir is currently unmanned but a new crew is scheduled to fly to 
the station in late august dunayev said 
