a new florida national guard helicopter 
crashed during a training exercise thursday killing one man and 
injuring another officials said 
the ah64 apache gunship helicopter went down at about 11 am 
during a flight from craig field in jacksonville to camp blanding in 
clay county said guard spokesman lt col ken forrester 
the army acquired the helicopter two months ago officials said 
investigators have not yet determined what caused the crash 
which occurred in far south jacksonville the spokesman said 
chief warrant officer bruce a pinner 44 of gainesville was 
dead at the scene pinner a vietnam veteran who had been with the 
guard for 10 years was the choppers copilot forrester said 
the pilot chief warrant officer david j mullen 30 of 
jacksonville suffered burns over 10 percent of his body and a 
fractured pelvis forrester said he was listed in fair condition at 
university hospital in jacksonville officials said 
a few hours after the accident all rescue personnel and others 
who ventured near the crash were checked for possible lung 
irritation from burning magnesium and aluminum in the aircraft 
forrester said 
no one suffered any serious smoke inhalation problems he said 
an army team from fort rucker ala was flown in to investigate 
the crash 
