<TEXT>
t boone pickens was joined by a group of japanese 
racketeers in seeking greater shareholders rights in koito 
manufacturing co but the corporate raider lost his bid for three 
board seats thursday even though he is the companys largest 
shareholder 
it was the most unusual shareholders meeting ive ever 
attended in my life said pickens who in march bought a 202 
percent stake in the automobile lighting manufacturer 
among the 200 shareholders present pickens was the only hand 
raised in favor of electing himself and two associates to koitos 
20member board 
during a 20minute address pickens said that japan should open 
up more and give foreign investors a chance to participate in its 
economy 
pickens said his inability to gain representation on the koito 
board showed that the japanese investment market is not as open to 
americans as the us market is to japanese 
you invest freely in my country yet i invest in japan and i 
am excluded he told shareholders at the threehour meeting 
but koito officials said their reluctance to support pickens was 
based on his history of corporate raiding in the united states not 
his being an american they said they doubted he had a longterm 
interest in the company and pointed to his lack of experience in 
manufacturing 
pickens said after the meeting he would testify before the us 
senate finance committee on july 11 about his difficulties in 
breaking into the japanese investment market 
the shareholders present included koito employees loyal to the 
company and racketeers known as sokaiya who generally took pickens 
side in their questioning and heckled koito executives in the end 
however they voted against pickens 
the sokaiya often speaking in the rough cadences of yakuza or 
gangsters scolded koito management for not thinking of japans 
international responsibilitiesand drew frequent laughter from the 
large contingent of japanese reporters watching on a television 
monitor in a nearby room 
sokaiya are a regular part of shareholders meetings of major 
companies in japan companies pay them to be quiet or sometimes to 
silence other shareholders 
although paying sokaiya is illegal industry sources say it is 
common to avoid filibusters by the racketeers who cannot be 
excluded because they are legal shareholders koito executives deny 
any ties with sokaiya 
pickens said the sokaiya asked good questions and criticized 
koito management for not answering them fully 
but he called the meeting something of a sham complaining 
that it was filled with koito employees who supported management 
statements almost as if theyd practiced 
after the meeting koito president takao matsuura said it was 
difficult to tell whether pickens intentions were those of a 
corporate raider 
mr pickens asked only very appropriate questions matsuura 
said 
koito was just one of more than 1500 companies holding annual 
meetings thursday and more than 5000 police were dispatched to 
prevent disturbances japanese firms are increasingly holding their 
meetings on the same day to discourage sokaiya but the result is 
that individual shareholders can attend only one or two meetings 
reducing their voice 
