<DOCNO> AP890629-0294 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the united states already the worlds largest 
debtor nation strengthened its hold on that dubious title in 1988 
as its foreign debt surged 41 percent to 5325 billion the 
government said thursday 
the commerce department releasing its annual balance sheet on 
americas global economic standing said the us debt burden had 
risen by 1542 billion in 1988 up from 3783 billion in debt to 
foreigners the united states owed at the end of 1987 
the figures mean that foreigners own more in us assets than 
americans own abroad the report was certain to fuel the already 
heated debate over whether the united states is losing control of 
its economic destiny to foreigners 
last year the government said that foreign holdings in the 
united states increased 154 percent to 1786 trillion american 
investments abroad rose a smaller 72 percent to 1253 trillion 
the difference between those two figures represents the united 
states net debtor position 
britain remained the country with the largest stake in the united 
states with 1019 billion in direct investment holdings up 28 
percent from 1987 japan moved into second place with 533 billion 
in direct holdings up a sharp 52 percent from 1987 
some economists predict that the debt total could surpass the 1 
trillion mark early in the next decade 
they warn that the burden of servicing that debt will put a 
severe strain on domestic resources lowering living standards in 
the united states as more and more money in the form of interest 
payments and dividends flows into the hands of foreigners 
we are exceedingly vulnerable as a country said c fred 
bergsten director of the insttute for international economics a 
washington research group 
we have a huge foreign debt and that means that decisions taken 
abroad can increasingly influence our own economy that is an 
untenable postion for a country that wants to be a global power 
the bush administration like the reagan administration before 
it played down the significance of the debt noting that it still 
represented a tiny fraction of americas 5 trillion economy and had 
nowhere near the adverse impact as the smaller total debt carried by 
third world nations such as brazil and mexico 
commerce secretary robert mosbacher said that the increase showed 
that america was still viewed by foreign investors as a good place 
to put their money 
it just shows that this country is where everybody wants to 
be he said in an interview with associated press radio 
commerce undersecretary michael darby noted that the united 
states was a net debtor from the revolutionary war until 1914 as 
foreigners provded the investment needed to develop america 
it foreign investment doesnt make you a weak nation it 
doesnt make you a strong nation darby said adding that what was 
important was for the foreign funds to be used to modernize american 
industry so that the country can compete in the global economy 
foreign direct investment defined as ownership of at least 10 
percent of a company soared by 21 percent last year to a record 
3288 billion as foreigners went on something of a buying spree of 
american companies 
one of the largest purchases was the 65 billion acquisition of 
federated department stores by the campeau corp of canada 
in addition to 10 percent ownership or more in companies direct 
investment includes holdings of office buildings and real estate 
the foreign purchases of american companies and choice real 
estate have set off alarms in congress rep john bryant dtexas 
is leading an effort to require better accounting of foreign 
ownership of us assets 
bryant contends that the true value of foreign holdings in the 
united states could be twice the official estimates because the 
commerce department is forced to rely on incomplete inaccurate 
information 
the new debt figure highlighted the speed at which americas debt 
is piling up 
as recently as 1983 the united states was the worlds largest 
creditor nation with an investment surplus of 89 billion that 
surplus fell to 33 billion in 1984 and disappeared in 1985 when 
the country became a net debtor for the first time in 71 years 
the change has occurred because the united states transferred 
billions of dollars into the hands of foreigners to pay for cars 
television sets and other imported goods those dollars are being 
reinvested by foreigners in the united states in everything from 
stocks and bonds to factories and real estate 
</TEXT>
